Dozens of patient stories hang from the roof of the Academy of Fine Arts' Project room gallery.
Each of them says Camille Auer's name.
The papers tell a multi-year story about how outside people have written down their interpretations of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he is.
"I wanted to tell you my personal treatment history to make the violence of the process visible," Auer says.
By process, he refers to the gender reassignment process.
It is often a year-long study period that includes appointments with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process will be initiated with a referral for "gender identity disorder" ­diagnosing studies carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
In Auer's case, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, he had used the estrogen he had ordered via the internet and was also very far along in his own repair process.
She felt that she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must go through the repair process so that the gender can also be corrected legally.
The Trans Act, i.e. the Act on the Confirmation of the Transsexual Gender (563/2002), obliges transgender people to be forced to undergo forced sterilisation in order to get the right gender to the Population Register Centre and passports, for example.
Currently, a psychiatric diagnosis and a certificate of infertility are required for each gender-remedial.
A person has the right to control their own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," says Auer.
The reform of the Trans Act has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has issued eight comments on the Act and the European Court of Human Rights has a preliminary ruling requiring the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to observe the right to self-determination.
Finland's previous government prepared a legislative amendment under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health Susanne Huovinen.
The elections and the Finns Party entered the government.
The change in the law is back to be stuck.
It is a matter of domestic political disputes that are not even related to this law.
"The government does not want to put it on the table, because there are disagreements within the board about changing the law," says Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty International's Finnish department.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the drugs used by Auer.
In the patient record installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of the transpol psychologist of Tampere University Hospital in Auer.
The psychologist met with Camille Auer twice and wrote a report based on these, which would define Auer's right to treatment and assistance.
The study's sense of reality appears to be vulnerable to faltering.
The researcher's perception of himself or herself appears in a boundary-level manner fragmented, and the unstable traits related to personality are emphasized.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed as mentally ill," Auer says.
It was an even greater shock when Auer was not granted gender reassignment treatment.
According to the medical staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
That's February 11, 2015, ­Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the TV in the transpol waiting lobby.
Later, a work of art called Monument for the Excluded was born on that television, in which Auer reflects on his experience of power and how to use it.
"It's crazy that anyone at birth as a woman can enlarge their breasts, but you need a diagnosis to remove your breasts," Auer says.
Your body is not your own if you feel that you are anything other than the number of your gender defined at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer's experience isn't the only one of its kind.
The gender reassignment process is harder for many for mental reasons than purely because of medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people who need to be justified of their own existence and their right to their own gender experience.
"It's crazy that people who need support and help are denied treatment, claiming that their resources aren't enough," Auer says.
Many people who have sought the process have psychological symptoms: depression, anxiety, possible bullying experiences.
On the basis of these, the medical staff may order that treatment cannot be started.
"Preventing treatment and getting help can put a person in an even worse situation than it was before the process began," Auer says.
Auer's personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition, Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and that is something that people usually find difficult to digest."
Depression has been treated with medication and when Auer started using hormones, it got easier.
He had finally been able to express the feelings that had existed since childhood and teenage years.
Why the wide jaw didn't seem to fit into your own body and why the chest muscles had to be round instead of a flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people around him who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using voice and movements," she says.
Today, Auer already feels seen, she exists as a woman.
However, in the early stages of the process, random comments from loved ones could hurt a lot.
What hurts the most is when your loved ones abuse you.
"They should know and they know who I am, but they won't agree or can't internalize it," he continues.
However, not all trans people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, that is, body conflict, where the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and a long research process, you cannot get official confirmation of your own gender.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, Parliament adopted a new procedure for the recognition of legal gender.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination in relation to the legal gender.
The adult applicant submits a written application for the new personal identity code, stating that they feel that they are of the other sex.
After a six-month period of reflection, the applicant confirms his/her application in writing and the Ministry gives the applicant a new personal identity code.
This right to self-determination is also required in Finland, and this requirement also sums up Auer's exhibition.
It has not been a therapy experience for the artist, but the exhibition is a political and artistic collection of works.
I want to believe that art still has weight and that it can bring about political changes, at a time when politicians have forgotten human rights.
