Civil rights organization issued a travel warning to Missouri
The National NAACP, a national civil rights organisation for African-Americans, has issued a travel warning for Missouri. This is due to the state’s discriminatory practices and the racist attacks that took place there.
“NAACP’s travel advisory for Missouri will come into force on 28.8.2017 and urges African-American tourists, visitors, and locals to pay special attention and to exercise extreme caution when traveling in a state where numerous questionable racial-based events have occurred recently,” the association said in a statement.
The law, which recently came into force in Missouri, makes it difficult to take discrimination cases to court. In addition, the implementation of state laws is disproportionately targeted at minorities. According to the NAACP, these factors led to the issuing of a travel warning.
“People’s civil rights are violated.
They are stopped based on their skin color and abused or killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
“We’ve never heard of such a few incidents in such a short time.”
The Missouri travel advisory is the organization's first warning about the U.S. state.
The organization cited as examples racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year. He was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel. He was arrested by Missouri police even though he was not charged with a crime.
A travel bulletin also referred to a report by the Missouri Attorney General that police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white driver.
“The purpose of the travel bulletin is to urge people to be on their guard and warn their families, friends, and co-workers about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to prepare, for example, by taking money to pay guarantees or telling relatives that they are going to travel through the state.”
According to the FBI, one hundred hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the sixteenth most of the U.S. states.
The travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri law, which makes it difficult for companies to sue for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
The ACLU, a constitutionalist organization, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they had passed immigration laws that oblige the police to arrest people for immigration violations. According to the organization, this increases racial profiling.
Generally, travel warnings are issued by the Ministry for Foreign Affairs and apply to other countries. Recently, however, NGOs have published them in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
