Poverty and Death in Indonesian Gold
Bardina Degei doesn't use a stove in cooking.
He rarely uses a pot.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in Indonesia's troubled province of Papua. When he prepares dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato – locally “nota” – directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the sweet potato burned on the carve is eaten greedily with bare, unwashed hands.
There's no furniture in Degei's home. He sits on a muddy ground floor, where he usually also does his daily chores, such as laundry in turbid water from a nearby swamp.
The office of the toilet is provided by a bucket in a room without a roof.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and she has not been assigned to take care of the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot. In addition, the soldiers must be taken into account.
“No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening,” Degei says.
This is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the Papua Highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969. The merger was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed the Dutch power, quickly turned its anger at the Jakarta government, which keeps the region firmly under control and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua. The eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotal is remote and dead. The journey there begins with an hour and a half flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues with a five-hour drive in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The city of about 19 000 inhabitants has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, the corrugated tin roofs of which have stained yellowish-brown.
Only a few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago tribes worshipped the god Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
“We didn’t have clothes like this,” Degei said. He means his colourful, hand-woven wrap-and-writting hat, dark skirt and brightly coloured sweater.
“We used to have only leaves covered our bodies.”
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia. 28 per cent of its population lives below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold country.
Paniai is a highland of about the size of New Jersey with a population of 153 000. Only about a hundred kilometers from Paniai is Grasberg, the world's largest and most profitable gold mine. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, United States.
In 2015, the mine produced 3.1 billion dollars worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated 78 billion dollar wood reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, as they mean the repressive presence of the strong Indonesian army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid local military personnel and local units in the military nearly 20 million dollars between 1998 and 2004. Individual officers were paid up to 150 000 dollars.
Papua's demands for greater sovereignty threaten this source of income, and they are silenced mercilessly.
According to human rights activists, the Indonesian army has killed more than 500 000 Papuans since 1969 and raped, tortured and captured thousands.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, mass killings in the Papuan Tribal Highlands in the 1970s took on the proportions of genocide.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in peaceful protests in the area.
The Brisbane Archdiocese Report We Will Lose Everything 2016 contains reports of the previous year's atrocities, such as executions without trial, torture – rape and electric shocks are particularly popular means – and from relentless attacks towards peaceful protests.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because there are cases every week,” said Andreas Harsono, a researcher at Human Rights Watch in Indonesia.
The screw has been tightened as Papua's natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, 83 per cent are Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslims are moving to the region from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi for a better livelihood.
The Javans' warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetable mix in peanut sauce.
It's hard for the locals to compete.
“Movers have started selling chicken and vegetables in the market at a lower price than the locals,” said 24-year-old Abeth You, who is from Paniai and moved to the provincial capital for work.
“Local women lost their clients.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – promised in his 2014 election campaign to address Papua’s injustices and human rights violations.
Papua consists of 29 areas, and this former carpenter won a vote in 27 districts, including Paniai, on his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokow in 2014 and we expected him to fulfill our hopes and restore justice,” You said.
Paniai experienced some kind of wave base just two months after the inauguration of Jokow in October.
Eleven children were singing Christmas carols by the campfire in Enarotal on 7.12.2014, when two Indonesian soldiers appeared on motorcycles from the dark.
The frightened children told the soldiers that they should be using headlights.
One of the soldiers did not like the remark. Local pastor Yavedt Tebai said the man returned with four soldiers.
According to the stories of the victims and witnesses, the drunken soldiers apprehended the children and beat them with rifles.
That's how one of the soldiers shot at the kids.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, fell into a coma as a result of the assault.
A couple of hours later, a building of the State Election Commission near the scene was set on fire, and the next day began to happen.
About a thousand Papuans – young men and women and children – gathered on the football field in front of a local police station and army command center to demand justice.
They were carrying hunting bows for celebrations, and they began to perform the traditional waita dance of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe, where they dance in a ring and imitate birdsong.
Some of the protesters began to stone the buildings of the police and the army.
As the mood heated up, the soldiers were ordered by the internal radio system: “If the crowds resist more than three times, shoot them to death.” The information is based on an official document seen by TIME magazine, which has not been made public to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the resident leader of the Kego Koto area, anticipated that the situation would get out of hand and asked the crowd to calm down and return to their homes.
No one wanted to listen anymore.
“When I turned around, I was shot on the left wrist,” he told TIME magazine on the porch of his wooden house, which was painted brightly.
Kayame still doesn't know who shot him, but the bullet came from the soldiers' ranks.
“A number of shots were fired in the crowd.”
Alfius Youwi was shot three times. His cousin saw the shootings.
“I ran to him and made sure it was really him,” Yohanes told TIME magazine, sadly. Like many Indonesians, he uses only one name.
“I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.”
Papua Police Superintendent Yotje Mende told reporters that the police were just “protecting” the police station because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Papua Police spokesman Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
“It’s about life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many injured.
The next day, information about the killings took place in Jakarta.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an emotional speech in Jayapura, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and promising that the violence in Papua would be tackled.
“I want the case to be investigated immediately so that nothing like this will ever happen again.”
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he would launch investigations into human rights violations outside the legal system.
However, he immediately began to withdraw his speeches.
“Most of the violations occurred a long time ago,
In the 1990's and early 2000's.
The most important thing is that we have decided to investigate the violations, but certain processes are needed for that,” he said.
In an interview with TIME magazine in Jakarta on 5.6.2017, Wiranto had already changed his mind. He said he wasn't going to start investigations in Papua.
“Everything will be dealt with in court,” he said.
The UN accuses Wiranto of “crimes against humanity.” The crimes relate to the deaths of more than a thousand people in the bloody independence referendum of East Timor in 1999. Wiranto told TIME magazine that 11 cases of human rights abuses in Papua have already been investigated, including the events of Paniai.
The families of the victims of Paniai are darkly incredulous about the claims.
“I’ve been interviewed four times in the past three years, but things haven’t progressed in any way,” Yohanes says.
“I’m tired of this.”
He says he still lives in fear, even though it has been years since the event.
“I’m scared,” he said.
“I’m afraid the army will arrest me. I’m afraid I’m going to be shot.”
His brother Yacobus confirms that the Panians are afraid to discuss the event.
He said the soldiers had assaulted him after he helped bury four of the victims.
“The soldiers were looking for me after the victims were buried,” he said.
The shootings haven't stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot and killed villagers in the neighboring Paniai district of Deiyai.
One was killed and 17 injured in a conflict between the villagers and the construction company's manager, which began when the manager refused to take the man who lost his consciousness to the hospital. There were also children among the injured.
The man who needed the hospital was 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who had been caught in the water while fishing on a nearby river. He died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers demonstrated at a construction site in front of the company's office.
According to the police, the villagers stoned the police, who responded with warning shots.
However, according to locals, the mobile police unit of the Indonesian paramilitary police opened fire on the crowd, killing one of the villagers.
“We are terrified. We’re afraid of revenge,” said 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being brought in for treatment.
“I’ve been hiding at home for two days.”
Deiyai's parliament has called for the police officers who fired the shots to be held accountable and the mobile police unit pulled out of the area.
Paniai has always been a problem for the Indonesian government.
The lack of real development feeds discontent in the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, who live in the lush central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of rebels who claim to be defending the rights of the Papuans with occasional attacks and kidnappings of Indonesian army soldiers.
Some of the leaders of the OPM are from Paniai, such as Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
The army has responded to the revolt by arbitrarily arresting and capturing thousands of people in Paniai in the name of “national sovereignty.”
Some of those arrested will never come back.
Among the Papuans, Paniai is known as “a sad, forgotten place.”
Poverty feeds discontent.
There is only a little rice for sale in Enarotal, and it is also too expensive for the locals,
Just like the bread.
People grow their food themselves: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, and one woman can be responsible for four or five fields of sweet potato.
Most of the harvest is for the family, and the rest is sold at the market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10 000 rupees (75 cents).
Over time, differences in the livelihoods of locals and migrants have widened, and the number of migrants has increased since new routes were opened to Nabire Airport.
There are few jobs, and they usually go to locals for better-skilled and wealthier migrants.
Only a few Papuans have sufficient capital and know-how to run their own business competitively.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village because there’s no work or money here,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
The remote Papua is overlooked around the world.
In addition, restrictions on international news coverage remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were expelled from Papua, although they had been granted a rare filming warrant. The official reason was the inability to cooperate with local institutions.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy director of Human Rights Watch Asia, Jokowi has not kept his election promises. He has not increased transparency or contributed to the development by removing the restrictions on news coverage.
“Reporters reporting on the restless eastern provinces of Indonesia, Papua and Western Papua, have new risks: denial of a visa and blacklisting,” Kine said in a statement.
The lack of freedom of the press means that the Indonesian government is only pressured by the immediate neighbours of Papua.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands – called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate Papua’s “numerous and widespread violations,” including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have traditionally also supported the Papua Liberation Movement.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir denied the accusations and told reporters in Jakarta that “Indonesia is still a democracy with freedom of the press, so it would be difficult to cover up evidence of human rights violations.”
The locals want foreign governments to intervene.
When the official Dutch delegation, chaired by human rights envier Kees Van Bar, visited Jayapura on 4.5.2017, the locals broke their silence and expressed their desire for freedom, said an anonymous source who attended the meeting.
There will be a presidential election in Indonesia in 2019, but the Papuans say they are no longer likely to vote for Jokow.
“Jokowi means well, but there are people around him who are involved in the Paniai shooting,” said Gobai, the president of the tribal council.
He wants Okow to know the situation of the Paniaists: they live under the power of a greedy and unpredictable army in need and poverty, practically without health services and educational opportunities.
According to Gobai, the Paniaists, like the other Papanists, consider the votes they have given to Jokow as a “debt” that must be repaid.
“They don’t want money. They just want justice,” he said.
Despite the threat and intimidation, the relatives of the victims of the Paniai shooting once more showed metaphorical resistance: they buried one of the victims in the country opposite the police station and the army office.
They know that they may never get justice, but at least they won't let those responsible forget their crimes.
“My family members were killed,” Yacobus said in a head.
“What else can we do?”
