However, the sighs of shock are genuine when the noose is threaded around the neck of the “Roger”.
Since 2005, human rights groups have returned to the Moore’s Ford Bridge to reframe the events of 1946. At the time, the Ku Klux Klan lynched two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey.
No one has been charged with the murders.
“It’s confusing that no one has been arrested in the years – even though the murderers live among us and many need to know who they are,” said Tyrone Brooks, who helps to re-set them.
“It’s a shame stain on history, but above all it’s a burden that weighs on our souls.”
Brooks is a 71-year-old civil rights activist and former Georgian congressman.
For him, re-staging is a startling call to action. It also reminds Monroe's residents that the injustice has never been corrected.
“We want the culprits to go to trial. We want things to finally be completed, and we want to recover from grief and make peace, but above all we want justice,” Brooks said.
“We cannot recover and make peace until we have justice.”
The coroner covers the body of the victim of the Georgian massacre on 27.7.1946.
According to FBI documents obtained by NBC, more than 50 men were suspected of lynching in Monroe and the surrounding counties.
No one was charged with murder.
Although the culprits have been free for decades, according to activists, the motives for the lynching have always been known to the locals: politics and sex.
In 1946, Georgian state blacks were allowed to vote for the first time in the presidential election. The Supreme Court issued its decision in April, and the election was held in the summer.
According to the FBI, there was an incident during the election in which a black tenant, Roger Malcom, stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, in a fight that apparently involved Malcom's wife, Dorothy.
According to Brooks, the city was rumoured that Hester had had an affair with Dorothy and that Dorothy was expecting a child for him.
According to FBI information, the influential white landowner Loy Harrison paid for Malcom's 600-dollar bail on 25 July 1946, against which he was released from prison.
On the way home, Malcom and Dorothy were accompanied by their cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
The crowd stopped their cars before the Moore’s Ford bridge.
“It turns out that Harrison ordered and arranged the murders,” the FBI said.
“It is also obvious that there was a conspiracy between the state and the local authorities. The authorities were involved in the murders and destroyed the evidence and did not reveal the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks puts it more succinctly.
“It was a suffrage murder,” he said.
“They were murdered because they wanted to send a message to black people that the same thing would happen to them if they were to vote.”
Cassandra Greene has been directing the re-staging of the Georgian massacre for almost a decade.
The performance is extremely realistic and captivating. It is a description of the shocking racism that many would like to believe has already disappeared from today's United States.
It's hard to watch the performance, but it's even harder not to see what Greene says is meant to be.
“We don’t want to talk about lynching because we would have to face our own dark sides,” the director says.
“But I can’t create a relationship with you if you can’t hear me or you don’t want to hear what I’ve been through.”
This year's rehearsal began in June. On the first day, about 30 actors – a dozen blacks and twenty whites – gathered to listen to Greene’s routine summary of the performance.
Wade Marbaugh is Greene's assistant director.
He has been playing the local Ku Klux Klan leader for years, but the role is always so difficult and disgusting.
“I feel dirty because I’m not myself,” Marbaugh said.
“However, it is important that this aspect of history is also kept on display so that it will never happen again.”
On the other side of the room, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, aka Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, practice their lines.
The show begins with a scene where Malcom screams and pushes Hester. He's furious that Hester's had a relationship with Dorothy.
“Didn’t you hear? I said get out of my mind, n---u!”
Rascona, or Hester, responds.
Then the punch goes.
And then everyone (at least all the black actors) bursts out laughing.
Greene laughs the hardest.
“What?!” Rascona asks.
He's confused.
“Did I accidentally hit too hard?” he asks.
“No,” Greene said.
“I just don’t think the Whites used the word n---u at the time.”
“Yes,” the other black actor confirms.
“It’s slang. You have to use a longer version.”
The subject of the performance is unpleasant, but the room is occupied by a friend spirit.
Everyone wants to succeed, and not just for the sake of the show. They want to honor the memory of those killed.
The scene starts over.
Now Rascona's words are slashing.
No one's laughing.
The re-staging stops quickly and violently.
Screaming, shots – and silence.
A woman dressed in a black funeral outfit stands next to the bodies and sings Billie Holiday's Strange Fruit.
His voice is broken for every other word.
A few dozen spectators a few dozen meters away wipes sweat and tears from their eyes.
Almost half of the audience is black and half is white.
Among them is a couple who have come to see a show from Ithaca in New York, but most are local.
They have been guided by Brooks to the graves of the victims in the oppressive humidity of Georgia.
The murders have come true from the story. The atmosphere at the scene is heavy.
After the singing performance, Greene invites the crowd to inspect the bodies.
The children squat down to look at the artificial blood and the still bodies and whisper to each other.
“They’re not really dead,” the little boy murmurs as if to remind himself.
In a few minutes, Greene will thank the audience.
The actors who played the lynchers take off their robes and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, a man from the local Ku Klux Klan leader.
Nick Rascona hugs two actors and then bursts into tears after a tough performance.
‘Don’t worry,’ said the woman in the show.
“We know you’re not him.
You did this for a good reason."
Later, the audience and the actors gather for a joint dinner.
The white couple who arrived from Altanta are busy discussing the performance with the black couple they have just met.
It's hard for Denise Duplinski to find the words when she describes the feelings that the show has evoked.
“It’s hard to listen to horrible words and watch terrible actions that people say and do, who look like you – precisely because they look like you,” he says.
“The show made me notice that lynchings are still happening,” he added. “They’re just called arrests.”
On the other side of the room, Brooks recalls the development of civil rights for listeners sitting at the same table.
He said he had already started planning next year's presentation.
“Restalling is a powerful experience because it depicts the horrors we’ve been through, but it’s also an educational experience,” Brooks said.
“Its message is that this can happen again if we don’t learn from it.
Those who do not know their history are doomed to repeat it.”
