New results of the Swedish asylum seekers' age tests announced
The latest results of the medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been announced. The results of the tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80 % of the tested were determined to be over 18 years of age. However, not everyone considers the tests to be reliable.
The Swedish National Forensic Agency began testing earlier this year.
The tests can be used to assess the age of asylum seekers more accurately than before. The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the real age of the applicants who claimed to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has so far commissioned 6 880 tests, and the Forensic Agency has now published the results of 2 481 tests. The tests were carried out between mid-March and the end of July in 2017.
Of those tested, 80 %, i.e. in 2002, asylum seekers were determined to be over 18 years of age. In addition, in 25 cases, the Forensic Agency determined that the test subject was “possibly 18 years of age or older”.
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the asylum seeker was “possibly under 18 years of age”.
The tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to suspect the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson from the Forensic Medicine Department says that the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
“The figures are fairly consistent. There are no major differences in the statistics of the previous months,” he told The Local.
Although a large number of applicants were determined to be over 18 years of age, this does not necessarily mean that applicants have lied to their age.
In May, the Agency published the results of the 581 tests and reported that 442 cases had “indications that the subject is 18 years of age or older.”
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that she was turning 18 this year.
In the medical age assessment method used in the tests, X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI images of the knee joints are taken. Then the dentists and radiologists analyze the images. The method has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is the endocrinologist of the Karolinsk Institute, Claude Marcus, whose work includes the assessment of human biological maturity. The assessment can be used to determine whether the person has reached adolescence earlier than usual or later.
“I’ve had a reason to think about it, and I don’t think the method used is the right way.
Determining the biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can’t determine the age, we shouldn’t pretend we can do it,” he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson, the Agency for Forensic Medicine, defended the accuracy of the tests: “In general, one can say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is small.
The risk is highest in a situation where the test subject will soon turn 18. The risk is about 10%.”
