Coe praises Russia’s “open-minded” apology for the doping scandal
Sebastian Coe, the world's athletics boss, praised the apology Russia made on Thursday for the doping scandal. However, Coe added that it was not yet time to lift Russia's ban on participation.
On the eve of the World Championships, Dmitry Shljahtin, the Russian Athletics Director, said at the IAAF Congress on Thursday that Russia's ban was appropriate and that he intends to fight doping with determination.
He said he was sorry for “all the athletes who were deprived of the gold or silver medal in the competitions.”
Despite his comment, the IAAF Congress voted to extend the ban. Russia was excluded from athletics competitions in November 2015 after a report by the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) presented evidence of state-subsidized doping in Russia.
“I think his response today was very direct. It was a very open-minded proposal,” Coe, the president of the IAAF, told reporters.
“The whole council and Congress were pleased that the Russian Athletics Federation admitted that the country had been through difficult times and announced that it would do everything possible to reorganize its activities.”
Coe said he was also “satisfied” with Russia’s acceptance of the terms of the ban.
“I think we had a very constructive day and progress has been made, but Congress supports the working group’s recommendation that now is not the right time to end Russia’s ban,” Coe said.
“We have to do everything we can in the coming months to normalize the situation.
The main principle has always been that we want to keep clean athletes separate from the corrupt system,” he added.
