How do the financial rules of football affect Neymar's move to Paris
The regulations restricting the use of money by European football clubs do not prevent Neymar's transfer from Barcelona, Spain, to Paris Saint-Germain, France. This is the most expensive transfer of all time.
Its possible consequences for Paris Saint-Germain (PSG) will be decided by the European Football Regulator UEFA, which may prevent teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
In 2011, UEFA introduced the financial rules of fair play. According to them, PSG must be able to demonstrate that the transfer of Neymar has been financed without major losses.
Barcelona was paid 222 million euros for the termination of the Brazilian contract, and Neymar's annual salary for the new club is in the tens of millions of dollars.
The transfer of Neymar to France involves a wide range of economic considerations.
PSG have no trouble paying Neymar's transfer amount and joins him in the star cast, as the club is funded by a family of rulers who have become rich with Qatari oil.
Clubs are allowed to spend large sums on the acquisition of players, but they must be balanced with real sources of income so that the football-related business is not loss-making.
The financial rules of Fair Play were drawn up on the initiative of Michel Platin, a Frenchman elected president of UEFA in 2007.
As a former footballer, Platini was of the opinion that the pursuit of success by indebtedness was cheating and led to serious problems if the banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, the focus of the fair game's financial rules shifted from club debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the implementation of the business model used by Roman Abramovich for the first time at Chelsea in 2003 was significantly more difficult. Abramovich bought a promising team, spent huge sums on player acquisitions and created a global brand.
The current three-year review period of the Fair Game Financial Rules will last until 2018. During this period, clubs may make a loss of up to 30 million euros.
Although Platini was forced to leave the role of UEFA chairman in a scandalous manner in 2015, his successor, Alexander Ceferin, also wants to curb the reckless spending of clubs.
“The fair game rules are still in use, and we will apply them in the future as well,” Andrea Traverso, who is responsible for the financial rules of fair play in UEFA, told the Associated Press news agency last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar out of their contract with a lump sum, it may appoint the amount in the accounting for the entire duration of his new contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer amount can be recorded as an annual fee of 44.4 million euros for the next five years.
Based on the fair game's financial rules, the first sanctions were handed out in 2014. The biggest sanctions were imposed on PSG and Manchester City, which is funded from Abu Dhabi.
PSG received a fine of 60 million euros, which was later reduced to 20 million euros. In addition, the club was ordered to limit its Champions League group to 21 players for the 2014–15 season instead of the usual 25 players.
UEFA monitors clubs that may attempt to circumvent its financial regulations by increasing their income through companies that are associated with club owners.
For example, if a Qatari company supports PSG but the value of the aid is considered to be above the normal level of the market, UEFA does not count the aid as the actual income.
This is what happened when UEFA decided in 2014 that the support of the Qatari Tourism Authority for PSG was excessive.
It has also emerged that some of Neymar's earnings could be financed by payments from the Qatar World Cup Organizing Committee for 2022.
However, the PSG and the organizing committee have denied that Neymar would be made an ambassador for the World Championships. It would be very easy for UEFA to reveal such an arrangement.
Due to PSG's previous sanctions, UEFA is following attempts to circumvent the rules even more closely than usual.
Sources informed the situation on Thursday that UEFA had not negotiated with PSG on the transfer of Neymar.
Sources gave an interview to the Associated Press on the condition that their identity is not disclosed because they have no authority to discuss the situation with PSG.
According to the latest published financial statements, PSG's net sales for the period 2015–2016 were 542.4 million euros and operating profit exceeded 10 million euros.
Last period's financial statements have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to attract new sponsors and increase the sale of club products and jerseys.
The club estimates that its turnover will increase by at least 30 per cent with the Neymar agreement.
Clearly irritated by the departure of one of the world's best players, the Spanish league tried to make it difficult for Neymar to move. It was alleged to violate the financial rules of fair play.
“This is a clear economic doping case for both the club and the state,” Spanish league president Javier Tebas told the Spanish newspaper AS. On the state, he referred to the Qatari ownership of PSG.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger also has reservations about the state's funding for the football club's activities. Arsenal is owned by an American sports tribe.
“The incident is the result of ownership that has completely changed the way football operates in the last 15 years,” Wenger said Thursday.
“Everything is possible after the state owns the football team.
It becomes very difficult to follow the fair game's financial rules. There are so many interests that are related to the fact that the famous player represents the state.”
