The Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that it will keep interest rates unchanged as economic growth has been impetuous and the easing of inflation has stopped speculation about interest rate hikes.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue to be slow. The bank shifted interest rate hikes because the income level of families is under increasing pressure.
The decision-makers of the Central Bank's Monetary Policy Committee decided by a vote of 6–2 to keep the interest rates at 0.25 per cent. The increase in the rate hike received less and less support this month because economic growth has been impotent.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank lowered its 2017 growth forecast to 1.7 per cent and its 2018 forecast to 1.6 per cent. It also warned that there is increasing pressure on household income levels, as inflation is expected to continue to accelerate to close to three per cent in the autumn.
However, according to the bank, interest rate hikes will be needed in the coming years to curb the inflation accelerated by Brexit. In addition, the Bank indicated that the borrowing costs may need to be increased more than expected in the financial markets.
In addition, the members of the committee decided to cancel part of the massive financial package, which began to be implemented a year ago in the aftermath of the Brexit referendum.
The Bank will discontinue the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide the programme with a low-cost financing of 15 million pounds, or a total of 115 million.
The minutes of the Bank’s interest rate decision state: “According to the forecast of the Committee responsible for monetary policy, the slow development of GDP will continue in the coming years, when the fall in households’ real incomes will reduce consumption.”
With regard to interest rates, the Bank reiterated the need for ‘some degree of tightening of monetary policy’ in order to curb inflation.
The market is currently forecasting the first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and the second in 2020.
However, the Bank stressed that any increases were ‘staggered’ and ‘limited’.
In May, the Bank forecasted growth of 1.9 per cent for this year and growth of 1.7 per cent for next year.
It now kept its growth forecast for 2018 at 1.8 per cent.
The pound weakened against the dollar and the euro as a result of the news.
Compared to the dollar, the pound weakened by 0.5 percent and was 1.31 dollars. Compared to the euro, it weakened by 0.4 per cent and was 1.11 euros.
The decision to keep interest rates unchanged was made after weaker than expected growth figures dampened the increased expectations of interest rate hikes. GDP grew by 0.3% in the second quarter and by 0.2% in the first quarter.
The Bank expects growth to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, but will pick up slightly at the end of the year.
Its latest inflation rate gave little hope to households suffering from accelerating inflation and low wage increases. According to the bank, the situation will worsen before it gets better.
The bank added that monetary policy ‘can’t prevent’ a decrease in revenue in the coming years. However, it expects that wage developments will recover ‘significantly’ at the end of the three-year forecast period.
The economy will also be strengthened by the strong increase in demand for British products as a result of the weak pound. It will override some of the impact of the decline in private consumption.
The decision was made one year after interest rates were lowered to 0.25 per cent after the shocked result of the EU referendum, which plunged the pound into a decline.
The Bank estimates that the overall impact of the decision is likely to be reflected in prices and the economy only after four years.
Before the central bank's latest decision, interest rate hikes had become increasingly louder as inflation tightened the pressure on households. Three decision-makers demanded a 0.5 per cent increase in interest rates in July.
Last month, inflation eased to 2.6 percent in June from 2.9 per cent. However, according to the bank, it was expected and inflation will intensify again in the coming months.
According to the bank, the overrun of its two per cent target was “whole” due to the weak pound.
