NHS prescribes 10 000 controversial HIV drugs
From September, patients may be prescribed a ‘reverse’ HIV anti-HIV medicine. The Supreme Court brought to an end to the dispute over the financing of the drug under the English Public Health System (NHS).
The NHS reported that pre-exposure prevention (PrEP) therapy is prescribed to approximately 10 000 people during the first three-year trial. Before intercourse, the drug has been found to reduce the risk of infection by approximately 86 % in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the experiment after the Court of Appeal upheld the Supreme Court's ruling last year. According to it, the NHS is able to pay for the PrEP drug, although it claims that local authorities should fund it.
Simon Stevens, the head of the English NHS, called Thursday’s decision a “significant new intervention,” and the national AIDS organization described it as “a crucial moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are the first to receive registrations for the experiment, which will expand to other clinics in October. The experiment will reach its full extent in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a prior-intercourse medicine that reduces the risk of infection.
Experiments have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infections in risk groups.
A drug taken before intercourse means that there are enough drugs in the body during intercourse that prevent HIV infection.
You can take the medicine daily or two hours before sex.
The target group of the treatment includes gay men, bisexual men and transgender people, as well as people with HIV positive partner who is not receiving effective treatment.
The clinics select candidates for the trial to meet the criteria for men, women and transgender people, as well as those whose HIV-positive partners are not known to receive antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and who have registered for the treatment of a general practitioner can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The program will cost 10 million pounds, and the English NHS signed a procurement agreement for medicines this week after an international tender.
The purpose of the experiment is to assess the potential of the PrEP drug by collecting extensive clinical evidence of its targeting, taking and treatment implementation.
“This important new intervention should complement and enhance the existing, and increasingly effective ways to prevent HIV,” says Stevens.
“That yet another significant achievement in the battle of more than 30 years in solving one of humanity’s greatest health challenges.”
“This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV,” said Deborah Gold, director of the national AIDS.
“If PrEP medication is targeted correctly at those who need it and those at risk, it could have a revolutionary effect on England’s HIV epidemic.
From September, those at risk will receive a medicine through a trial funded by the NHS, the use of which they can decide independently without the need to consult with a partner. It has an empowering effect that will improve the lives of a great many people.
This was welcome news.”
“The most important thing now is to ensure that the experiment is launched quickly throughout the country and that no one at risk is left out of it,” said Ian Green, director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
“The PrEP drug used in the experiment has been acquired, and we will soon be able to protect ten thousand people in high-risk groups from HIV infection.”
“The start of the PrEP experiment is a welcome event that was prolonged in vain by several months due to the government’s slowdown,” said Sharon Hodgson, the shadow government’s health minister.
“We have evidence that the medicine can have a revolutionary effect on the work we do to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
The experiment will help us to better understand the real benefits of the PrEP drug.
It is now important that the experiment is launched as soon as possible throughout the country. In this way, we can protect those exposed to HIV and get another step closer to a situation where the spread of HIV in society has been stopped.”
