He must be prepared for activism and organization, but he must also be familiar with the different layers and circumstances of the experience of living in black. And he needs to know what we need to do to free ourselves.
Even though I've been able to protect her from blatant racism, she's still like the rest of the black girls.
I feel like I would harm him if I protected him from reality.”
Their first stop in Ferguson was the South Florissant Road, which is located opposite the police station. It became a camp for activists as they waited for information on the case and eventually learned that no charges would be brought against the police.
From there, Ferrell and his daughters went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to the protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to take a new approach to activism.
“My activism changed completely after August 9,” he said. While studying at the University of Missouri, St. In Louis, Ferrell was president of the Association of Minority Nurse Students. At the time, he focused on food law and health ingests in black communities.
“I had no experience of organizing.
Somehow it just happened.”
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the assistant director of the documentary.
Folayan said he and cinematographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar “just wanted to tell” what was happening.
There was a suspicion in Ferrell's mind. He asked, “Do you really want to tell us what’s happening, or do you want a story that you can take advantage of?”
The suspicion was caused by the countless times that people, usually whites, had appeared in the local community, who only wanted to benefit from its difficulties and persistence.
“We had heard that those born and raised in Ferguson did not have a common voice,” Folayan said in a recent interview. “We wanted to do things differently.”
Folayan had already contacted Deputy Director Damon Davis, known for his activism among death-sented prisoners.
Davis's presence prompted Ferrell to join the project along with six other locals. The crew followed the events in the years following Brown's shooting.
“This isn’t a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, we speak,” Davis said.
“The most important thing for me was how the local people are portrayed in the film, because I’m portrayed the same way.”
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell’s experience, because it was wanted to show that the popular movement “is not about a charismatic leader but a community.” However, Ferrell proved to be the most open of the photographs.
That's why the documentary features surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and getting married.
“I felt pretty naked,” Ferrell laughs as he told me what it felt like to see the movie for the first time.
“But I understood that this work and the humanization of blacks requires a certain vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell's story recounts and brings the role of black queer women to the centre again in the larger Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was created on social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after police shot and killed black teenage boy Trayvon Martin in 2012. Two of the movement's three founders identify with the queer identity.
“The leadership of black queer women has kept the whole movement going,” says Ferrell. “It’s because we have to fight constantly on many fronts.
Black queer women have had to endure everything.”
Folayan agrees: “The movement is indeed sustained by black women, among whom there are a lot of queer women.”
However, he emphasizes that Ferrell was not selected for the documentary “self-purposedly” because of his queer identity.
“He got the energy moving,” Folayan said.
“It’s no coincidence that he was on the front line. Black queer women live at the intersection of many things, and they have a lot at stake.
His energy is transmitted from the big screen.”
The film crews have long since left Ferguson, but relations between the community and the police are still strained.
Ferrell still has two and a half years of parole left. He was convicted of blocking the highway at a demonstration.
His description of the social political climate in his home neighborhood is brief and concise: “A mess.”
Yet he still trusts the slogan he learned by heart on the streets of Ferguson three years ago:
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We can only lose our chains.”
A suitable resemblance: the artist creates portraits of Chelsea Manning's DNA
The Fridman Gallery in New York has a face hanging in the middle of the exhibition space – white, black and brown faces, between which you can see a resemblance.
These 30 works are portraits of the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg, based on DNA samples taken from Chelsea Manning's cheek and hair.
Manning sent samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where he served his 35-year sentence. Manning was convicted of leaking classified diplomatic telegrams to WikiLeaks.
Dewey-Hagborg's A Becoming Resemblance exhibition was opened on 2.8.2017.
It is based on two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg and Manning. Dewey-Hagborg combines technology, information technology and art. Manning is a trans woman and groundbreaking dissident whose prison sentence was lifted by Barack Obama on the third last day of his term.
Dewey-Hagborg analyzed Manning's DNA algorithmically and created 30 portraits based on his genetic data. They are a sharp, albeit somewhat theoretical statement on the adaptability of DNA data, ambiguity and the cause-and-effect relationships and identity behind the interpretations.
Chelsea Manning, born Bradley Edward, has openly stated that she has identified with women since puberty. In 2013, he was found guilty of 20 counts of offences, including violation of the Spying Act, computer fraud and theft.
There was only one picture of the prison-convicted Manning: a grainy, black-and-white selfie in which the bothered Manning sits in the driver's seat in the car. He's wearing a platinum-blond wig that became his hallmark.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg had the hugely popular Stranger Visions project, which he carried out in 2012.
In it, he created portraits based on forensic data. He received DNA data on, for example, cigarette butts and chewing gum and created pictures of what the people in question might have looked like.
Then the artist received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning and needed a picture of the story,” Dewey-Hagborg told a new show.
You couldn't visit Manning and you couldn't film him in prison. So the magazine contacted Chelsea and asked if she would be interested in making a DNA portrait of Manning.
The artist and his imprisoned muse suddenly became correspondents. They wrote to each other for a couple of years.
They even made together a Suppressed Images comic book illustrated by Shoili Kanungo. It described a future in which the president would have eased Chelsea's sentence and he would have access to the exhibition.
In reality, Obama shortened Manning's sentence just a few days after the comic book was published. It was a lucky coincidence after seven tough years in a national military prison.
It is also impressive that the exhibition is opening right now, when Donald Trump is waging his own war against information leakers and transgender soldiers, and is coming up with more and more new ways on Twitter to reinforce the powerful divisions he actually had to ease.
Dewey-Hagborg believes that “everything has a purpose.”
On the gallery wall is the artist's statement and under it is Manning's great autograph, where the point of the last name i is the heart. In his statement, the artist calls for an end to “the automatic division on which gender, race, sexuality and culture have been based.”
On the opposite wall is the DNA sequence of Manning: a long sequence of letters C, G and A written with a pencil.
With this combination of 200 letters – or a nucleotide, as the scientific definition used by the artist – Dewey-Hagborg wants to illustrate how similar we are all, at least from our biology.
“I hope my exhibition will help people understand that we are genetically equal and that genetic information is very personal and open to interpretations,” says Dewey-Hagborg. The exhibition also features his 2007 video work Spurious Memories.
“DNA tells countless stories. There are 30 of them here.”
The last work of the exhibition is in its own room: a page from the comic book of Manning and Dewey-Hagborg.
In it, Manning's figure rises from prison like King Kong, holding a megaphone.
“If they can shut you up, they’ve won,” the picture reads.
“Never be silent.”
“The text is from a letter I received from Manning,” says an artist from Philadelphia.
“It’s so impressive that I still get chills.”
Contrary to what was described in the comic book, Manning has not yet seen the exhibition. When Manning shows up, he is greeted by a face based on his own genetic data, like a group of protesters in the middle of the showroom.
It is intentional, like everything else in this exhibition: for example, the DNA sequence of Manning is written with a pencil at a height that is the same as his length (157.5 cm).
“My face used to be on the wall, but I wanted to bring a sense of crowd to them,” says Dewey-Hagborg.
“I wanted to film the mass movement that Chelsea had created, which was also behind his release.”
