It recently signed with Uber.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to conduct customized surveys, collect responses confidentially in real time, and map problem areas.
In addition, employees can report inappropriate behavior anonymously by text message.
And if there is reason to suspect the manager of inappropriateness, the complaints go directly to the company's board.
“General opinion has overthrew the authorities,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
He points out that if a company treats its employees badly or acts unethically, the consequences can be costly, even if the authorities do not intervene. Consumers can start boycotting the company, and it can also lose employees and be sued.
