This isn't Rhodes' first book based on archives. In 2014, he published Dead Men’s Teeth and Other Stories, whose inspirations were documents from the National Library of England. The project was emotional.
“I was in tears when I noticed the thumbprint in the letter. The letter was written by a double agent who worked for Jacobites in the 17th century,” Rhodes says.
“It was his fingerprints.
And the letters smell of smoke, because at that time fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the smell makes the reader feel that he is on the spot himself.
I love the archives!”
The author, who was attracted to old documents, was allowed to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust and the National Arts Council of England, which felt too good to be true. He admits that he could not be in the castle for a little longer than he had hoped.
He spent the days exploring the Victorian “new” castle, archives, treasures, and rarities, such as hyena heads hung on the walls and bottles that had been in the moat for centuries.
He toured the ruins and estates of the old castle and talked with forest keepers, gardeners and sometimes illustrative artists.
In the evenings, he “took whiskey and started writing.”
The nearer history of Scotney is quite unknown, as the castle was completely transferred to the National Trust Foundation only after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about ten years later, the foundation's staff was just about to start going through the archives. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: by taking everything extra to the attic.
The archives contained diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, and maps of who owned what. “You could imagine that the land disputes are boring,” Rhodes says. “Here, however, families even fought for one birch tree.
I thought I should let it be.”
Some of the stories in the book proceed from castle to English history, such as The Labourer. It tells the story of a man who joins the English peasant revolt in 1381 shortly after the castle was completed.
“Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex mentions that there was a riot in the castle in 1380,” Rhodes said.
“The peasant rebellion of England began in the same area, and it came to mind that the revolt could begin with a riot.
“Maybe these events are connected?”
The other stories in the book are closely related to the history of the castle – such as The Priest, the story of a priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler tells the story of the smuggler Arthur Darrell from the 17th century. He is said to have staged his own funeral by filling the coffin with stones (it was noticed years later when his grave was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family in Scotney. “The men of the family seem to have been quite a rogue. They were constantly in debt and bought things they could not afford.
The men of the Darrell family solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy old women. I see them as handsome guys who knew how to court the heiress.”
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about the Life's Hound, a sanatorium that operated in the early 20th century, of which only a eutrophic plot remains.
Scotney Castle has a special place in his heart.
“It was sad to leave,” he said.
“I didn’t want to go back to this damn life.”
