Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares of the digestive system.
However, a recent study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects approximately 1.3 million people in the United States and 300 000 people in the United Kingdom. It causes stomach cramps, bloating, frequent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with irritated bowel syndrome are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen intestinal tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, the head of the study, the immune cells guard the intestine and ensure that harmful microbes that are hiding in food cannot enter the body.
Inflammatory cells are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance drops too close to the inflammation, the result may be irritable bowel syndrome.
The experiments found that there are immune cells that strengthen tolerance in mice whose guts contain a certain bacteria.
This bacteria needs tryptophan in order for immune cells to appear. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
“We found a link between the development of Lactobacillus reuteri and cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal microbiome of the gut,” says Professor Colonna.
“The more tryptophan there was in the mice diet, the more immune cells they had.”
If the same works in humans, the combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammatory sensitivity.
While studying the immunity-boosting immune cells, Postdoctoral Researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mouses had such cells, they did not exist in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiomes of the mice, i.e. the normal bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the intestinal DNA of the mice was examined, six bacterial species were detected in the mice that had immune cells but not other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice that had no gut microbioma and did not develop immune cells in a sterile environment, immune cells began to appear.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in the liquid and transferred small amounts of fluid – without bacteria – from mice to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells evolved into cells that strengthen tolerance.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, known as indol-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the number of cells that strengthen tolerance increased by about 50 percent. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells decreased by half from the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same tolerance-boosting cells as the mouse, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan from Lactobacillus reuteri will make the cells develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, genotic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in patients with irritable bowel syndrome.
“We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the internal surfaces of the intestines,” says Cervantes-Barragan.
‘A high level of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuteri may contribute to their increase.’
