The White House exhibit paid thousands of dollars to the taxpayers
The White House's decision last month to fly a naval helicopter to the White House's southern lawn, presenting American production, was to pay taxpayers 24 000 dollars. The information is evident from the military documents received by TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter is called Marine One when the president is on board. It was attraction at the event held at the White House on 17.7.2017, where American construction programs were presented.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a group of White House officials familiarized with the products from all 50 states.
In addition to the helicopter produced in Connecticut, the display included a sailboat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
The White House military office had requested the helicopter to be replaced by a mission order only about 36 hours before it landed on a southern lawn for an “exceptional” event. This is evident from the documents of the Navy's HMX-1 helicopter squadron.
“I just wanted to make sure you were aware of it, because it’s an extraordinary event that gets a lot of visibility,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, who is the deputy commander of the Navy Air Force.
The message said that the helicopter would arrive at the southern lawn on 17.7. at seven in the morning and the event would start at three in the afternoon. The helicopter would leave the scene only after the grassy field was emptied between six and nine in the evening.
The message also mentioned that if the helicopter's departure from the White House was delayed, another crew would be needed due to service time restrictions.
The original crew was in the helicopter during the incident, and the unit's security personnel were at the helicopter's house when it was on the ground.
The documents received by the TIME magazine do not reveal whether another crew was eventually needed.
The U.S. Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 asked if the event violated the law.
“One of our questions was whether this violated the Hatch Act. We were told not to be violated,” the commander wrote.
“It sounds like you can participate,” the deputy commander replied.
Made in America was the official event of the White House, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even the official events have political tones.
At the event, the president spoke in favour of the health care reform that was under the Senate proceedings at the time and looser state regulation.
The use of the Marine One helicopter and the Air Force One aircraft for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must use them on their travels,
But using them only for photographs is unusual.
Trump's actions attracted attention in February when Air Force One rolled into the background of the presidential campaign event in Melbourne, Florida. Trump has strongly criticized the use of his predecessor's presidential plane on Twitter.
“The White House is very pleased with the Made in America event, which showcased products made by American workers from all 50 states,” said White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
The crews of the HMX-1 regularly make training flights in the Washington area and practice bringing the president to the White House with centimeters of precision on the southern lawn.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training sessions for the White House.
According to one official, the flights to Made in America included the crew's monthly training quota.
That day, the unit’s helicopters also flew for 11 hours on “non-presidential support missions.”
According to the White House, the incident did not cost taxpayers any other costs.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in the helicopter's presentation on the White House's southern lawn.
HMX-1 has no records of flights related to the President's duties, and it is difficult to accurately estimate the cost of the event.
According to the Ministry of Defence's hourly allowances for 2017, the replacement level of the VH-3D helicopter is 24 380 dollars per flight hour.
According to documents from the HMX-1 unit, the flights from the Quantico base in Virginia to the White House and back took a total of one hour.
According to the White House, the operating costs of the helicopter are clearly lower.
“Calculating the cost to taxpayers according to the level of compensation is misleading,” Walters said.
‘The estimated level of compensation includes staff, maintenance and many other so-called embedded costs, which are taken into account in the annual appropriations.’
According to a study conducted by the RAND research company in 2015, the compensation levels do not include personnel costs, but they take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time of the incident, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter at the event.
“The idea is to introduce American production,” Spicer said.
“I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to be involved in ensuring national security and will probably employ hundreds or thousands of people.
And I think that, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that many Americans have worked hard for.
It is entirely appropriate to bring it up.”
It is not certain whether Trump visited the helicopter during the incident, but at least he sat down at the scene of the fire truck driver.
