GMB is concerned about the continued operation of the McVitie’s factory in Scotland
The union is seeking confirmation from McVitie’s brand manufacturer’s leaders for long-term commitment to production at the Glasgow plant.
According to the Scottish section of the British General Trade Union (GMB), the company has not announced its plans for the future of the Tollcross plant.
The Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits and other products factory has more than 500 employees.
Pladis, which owns the McVitie’s brand, said it had invested more than five million pounds in the factory in recent years.
The company added that employees and trade union representatives will be “will certainly be told first” if there are any changes in operations.
In a letter to the factory manager, GMB urges the company to “respond to the concern that no funding has been allocated to modernisation of production lines.”
Drew Duffy of the GMB Trade Union finds it very worrying that the factory manager does not provide clear information about Tollcross's business needs and future investment plans.
“Families have worked here from generation to generation, and the workforce is heavily concentrated in the local community and the Glasgow metropolitan area. The factory is a significant employer in the area of high unemployment and poor livelihood.
From the point of view of jobs, wages and livelihoods, and the continuous reduction of Brexit, rising living costs and production, eastern Glasgow is in dire need of successful McVitie’s production.”
According to a Pladis spokesperson, the factory manager had received a trade union letter the day before and the company responds directly to the letter because it values constant interaction with employees and trade union representatives.
“We had a regular meeting with employees and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, when we openly discussed several issues.
